                        "title":  "A Simple Framework For Writing Blog Posts",
                        "chunk":  "blog post starts with a story that helps to ground the reader in what youГўВҖВҷre about to teach them and why they should care. A sentence should be enough. Just enough so that you can remember the story you want to tell. You might want to go a little more in depth if youГўВҖВҷre afraid you wonГўВҖВҷt remember. For instance, in my post ГўВҖВҳwhat are teeny tiny goalsГўВҖВҷ I noted that IГўВҖВҷll tell a story about how teeny tiny goals changed my life. I know which story I want to tell and IГўВҖВҷm confident I wonГўВҖВҷt forget. But if I wasnГўВҖВҷt so sure, I might add another sentence or two. IГўВҖВҷm a Teacher Writer and like most Teacher Writers, the story is the hardest part for me. I get so excited about just sharing my idea, I forget IГўВҖВҷm a storyteller first. And that the story is important to the reader. (I had to go back in and add a story to this post, after IГўВҖВҷd written it. And I actually wrote ABOUT adding a story in this post. See what I mean?) Subheads This is the hardest part. YouГўВҖВҷll have to think about your premise and what it is you want to tell your reader. What do you want them to know? DonГўВҖВҷt worry about writing perfect subheads that youГўВҖВҷll actually use in your story. Just write a few words or a sentence that will remind you of the sections you want to include in your post. This is a loose outline of your post. Here are the subheads for my post about teeny tiny goals. Screenshot: Author IГўВҖВҷm quite sure those wonГўВҖВҷt be my actual subheads ГўВҖВ” but they could be. When I look at them, I can see the structure of my post, with a story at the top and a take away rounding the whole thing out. IГўВҖВҷve given myself enough information so that writing this will be significantly easier than just looking at a blank page. All I need to do is fill out each section with two or three paragraphs. I havenГўВҖВҷt over thought the whole thing. This doesnГўВҖВҷt have to be a detailed outline that you could turn into your sophomore English teacher for a grade. Just a few words is enough, I promise. Take Away The last part of your post is the take away. What do you want your readers to come away from your post with? It might be any of these: Solidarity ГўВҖВ” just the knowledge that they arenГўВҖВҷt alone. This is common with personal essays, in particular. The ability to go out and do a thing. This is common for how-to or DIY posts. A particular feeling or emotion ГўВҖВ” hope, escape, desire, etc. Information that they came for. For instance, if you were writing a book review, the take away would be a recommendation for or against the book. A tool or other resource tied to your post. Sometimes the take away is explicit. YouГўВҖВҷll end with a paragraph that tells the reader exactly what you hope theyГўВҖВҷll do",
